    <!-- AFFILIATE DISCLAIMER -->
    <AffiliateDisclaimer />

    <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
    <h2 id="why-multivitamin">Why 9 Out of 10 Americans Have Nutritional Gaps</h2>

    <p>The American diet is simultaneously calorie-rich and nutrient-poor. Despite spending more on food than any previous generation, the majority of adults fail to meet the Recommended Dietary Allowance for multiple essential vitamins and minerals. This paradox is driven by three converging factors: the dominance of ultra-processed foods (which make up 58% of calories consumed), declining soil mineral content that has reduced the nutrient density of produce by an estimated 5-40% since the 1950s, and lifestyle factors like chronic stress and medication use that increase nutrient depletion rates.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">92%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of American adults have at least <strong>one vitamin or mineral deficiency</strong>, according to analysis of NHANES data published in the <em>Journal of the American College of Nutrition</em>. The most prevalent deficiencies include vitamin D (42%), vitamin E (91%), magnesium (52%), calcium (44%), and vitamin A (40%).</p>
    </div>

    <p>A multivitamin gummy does not replace a healthy diet — but it does serve as nutritional insurance that closes the most common gaps. The gummy format adds a compliance advantage that tablets cannot match: research shows that adults are 30-40% more likely to take a gummy supplement consistently versus a traditional pill, and daily consistency is the single most important factor in supplement effectiveness.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>What to Look For</strong>
        <p>Third-party testing (USP, NSF, or ConsumerLab), bioavailable forms (methylfolate, methylcobalamin, D3), at least 100% DV for vitamins D and B12, and fewer than 3g added sugar per serving. Avoid proprietary blends that hide individual doses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>What to Avoid</strong>
        <p>Mega-doses above 300% DV of any single nutrient (unnecessary and potentially harmful for fat-soluble vitamins), artificial colors and flavors, and products without verifiable third-party testing. Also beware of products that require 4+ gummies per serving — the cost per actual day of use becomes unreasonable.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>The Gummy Limitation</strong>
        <p>Most gummy multivitamins exclude iron and calcium because iron tastes metallic and calcium requires too much space per dose. If you need supplemental iron or calcium, take them as separate tablets. Also note that gummies have a shorter shelf life (12-18 months) than tablets (24-36 months) due to moisture content.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="target" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Bioavailable Forms Matter</strong>
        <p>Methylfolate (5-MTHF) is absorbed by 100% of the population, while folic acid requires MTHFR enzyme conversion that 40% of people have impaired. Methylcobalamin is the active form of B12. Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is 87% more potent than D2. These forms cost marginally more but deliver significantly better results.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2020 randomized crossover study published in the <em>Journal of the American College of Nutrition</em> found that <strong>gummy multivitamins raised serum levels of vitamin D3, vitamin B12, and folate</strong> comparably to tablet multivitamins over a 4-week period. The study concluded that the gummy format does not compromise nutrient delivery when products are properly formulated and dosed.</p>
      <cite>J Am Coll Nutr, 2020 — Randomized crossover bioavailability study</cite>
    </div>

