    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Multivitamin Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do multivitamin gummies actually work?</summary>
      <p>Yes, multivitamin gummies effectively raise serum levels of key nutrients when properly formulated. A 2020 study in the <em>Journal of the American College of Nutrition</em> confirmed that gummy multivitamins deliver vitamin D, B12, and folate comparably to tablet forms. The key is choosing products with adequate doses of bioavailable nutrient forms and taking them consistently every day.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What should I look for in a multivitamin gummy?</summary>
      <p>Prioritize third-party testing (USP, NSF, or ConsumerLab), bioavailable vitamin forms (methylfolate, methylcobalamin, D3), at least 100% DV of vitamins D and B12, and fewer than 3g added sugar per serving. Avoid proprietary blends and products requiring more than 3 gummies per serving.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why are iron and calcium missing from most multivitamin gummies?</summary>
      <p>Iron has a metallic taste that cannot be masked in gummy form, and calcium requires doses too large for a gummy matrix. A 500mg calcium tablet would require 4-6 gummies to deliver the same amount. If you need supplemental iron or calcium, take them as separate tablets alongside your gummy multivitamin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many gummies should I take per day?</summary>
      <p>Most multivitamin gummies require 2 gummies per serving. Always check the supplement facts panel — taking only 1 gummy when the serving size is 2 delivers half the labeled nutrients. Some premium products require 4-6 gummies per serving. Do not exceed the recommended serving size, as fat-soluble vitamins can accumulate.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are gummy multivitamins better than tablets?</summary>
      <p>Neither is categorically better. Gummies offer better taste and 30-40% higher compliance rates. Tablets deliver higher doses, more minerals, and lower cost per serving. For most adults, the daily consistency advantage of gummies outweighs the theoretical nutrient density advantage of tablets.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take a multivitamin gummy?</summary>
      <p>Take with a meal containing dietary fat to maximize absorption of fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K. Breakfast or lunch is preferred because B-vitamins can mildly stimulate energy, potentially affecting sleep if taken late in the evening.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do I need a multivitamin if I eat a healthy diet?</summary>
      <p>Even with a balanced diet, 92% of Americans have at least one nutrient deficiency. Soil depletion, food processing, and increased nutrient demands from stress make complete dietary coverage difficult. A multivitamin serves as nutritional insurance — most valuable for individuals with dietary restrictions, limited food variety, or elevated demands.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are multivitamin gummies safe for everyday use?</summary>
      <p>Yes, multivitamin gummies formulated at or near 100% DV are safe for daily long-term use in healthy adults. Water-soluble vitamins (B, C) are excreted when consumed in excess. Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) can accumulate but gummy doses are typically well below toxicity thresholds. The primary safety concern is overconsumption — store gummies out of reach of children.</p>
    </details>

